    "summary": "The Behistun Inscription (c. 520–518 BC) is a multilingual royal inscription carved into a cliff face at Mount Behistun in modern Iran by Darius the Great, recording his legitimation of power and military victories in three languages — Old Persian, Elamite, and Babylonian — and serving as the key that unlocked the decipherment of cuneiform writing in the 19th century.\n\nCarved at a height of over 100 meters in the cliff face of the main road between Mesopotamia and Iran, the inscription was designed to be visible to all travelers but practically impossible to reach and deface. The text describes Darius's accession to the Persian throne and his suppression of multiple revolts across the empire. Its significance to modern scholarship lies in its trilingual nature: when the British officer Henry Rawlinson copied and translated it in the 1830s–40s (at considerable personal risk), the Behistun Inscription played the same role for cuneiform decipherment that the Rosetta Stone ([[event:1047|Rosetta Stone Creation]]) had played for Egyptian hieroglyphics — providing the key to reading a lost script by comparison with known languages. Its decipherment opened the entire corpus of Mesopotamian literature, law, and history to modern scholars.",
